Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 51.5 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 55.3 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: PM2.5 (ug/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.670)

Key Characteristics

  • Cultural capital with severe health challenges. Highest COPD rates in India (19.3%)
  • Extreme urban density impact on health
  • Kolkata will demonstrate how extreme urban density creates severe health crises even with world-class medical infrastructure
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

  • Population: ~15.8M (metro), ~4.5-6.6M (city); extremely high density 24,000/sq km; sex ratio 908/1000; high literacy rates
  • Respiratory Disease: Very high burden—COPD 19.3% overall (23.7% males, 14.5% females), asthma 26.54%; 25% of hospital patients have respiratory diseases; multiple active viruses (RSV, influenza A, rhinovirus)
  • Healthcare: 48 government hospitals, 366 private facilities; 61 beds per 10,000 people (above national average); 120+ healthcare facilities with 18,000+ bed capacity; 10 medical colleges; 78% prefer private care
  • Seasonal Patterns: Respiratory infections surge during temperature fluctuations, winter, and post-monsoon; recent spikes from weather yo-yo effects and seasonal virus transitions
  • Socioeconomic: GDP $220 billion (2024); major economic hub with stock exchange; 40%+ informal sector employment; 83.7% work in tertiary sector; significant urban density challenges
